article.description:
Rookie Caron Butler scored a season-high 25
points and put Miami ahead for good midway through the second
quarter as the Heat defeated the struggling Toronto Raptors 97-77
Friday night.
article.headline: Rookie Butler scores season-high 25 points in rout
article.linkText: Butler's all-around effort sparks Heat over Raptors
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Lenny Wilkens believes the Toronto Raptors reached a new low with a 20-point loss to the lowly Miami Heat. "This game was the worst we've played, it was just awful,'' Wilkens said after Miami defeated the Raptors 97-77 Friday night, sending Toronto to its sixth loss in seven games. Rookie Caron Butler scored a season-high 25 points and put Miami ahead for good midway through the second quarter as the Heat had its most lopsided victory of the season. Butler, chosen 10th overall in the draft, finished 8-for-16 from the field and 9-for-10 from the line with six rebounds, three assists and three steals. His four free throws and jumper at the end of the third quarter gave Miami a 26-point lead -- its biggest of the game. Butler's previous high was 20 on Dec. 2 at Phoenix. "It was a great night offensively,'' Butler said. "I was just knocking down shots. I've been working very hard on my shot.'' Eddie Jones added 17 points for the Heat, who have won three of four. Miami shot 56 percent to Toronto's 37 percent and outrebounded the Raptors 48-36. "Your pride has got to take over. We let them box out, guys penetrated, we were horrendous,'' Wilkens said. Voshon Lenard had a team-high 19 for the Raptors, who were without leading scorer Vince Carter and leading rebounder Antonio Davis. "That was about as bad a game that I've probably been involved in,'' said Toronto's Morris Peterson, who shot 1-for-10 with five fouls. "It was ugly.'' Jones, who didn't play in the fourth quarter, scored eight points as Miami finished the first half with a 12-2 run to take a 53-37 lead. Miami outscored Toronto 30-12 in the second quarter, and Jones had 15 points at intermission. "They didn't have their two best players and we took advantage,'' Jones said. The Heat, who won consecutive games for just the second time this season, made their first six shots of the game. "We had a rough start, a rough middle and a rough end,'' Toronto's Michael Bradley said. Game notes
Hulk Hogan and wrestling manager Jimmy "Mouth of the South'' Hart sat courtside. Hogan wore a Raptors jersey. ... Toronto center Nate Huffman missed the game with a sore right knee. ... Miami plays New York and Cleveland in the last two games of its trip on Sunday and Monday, while Toronto hosts the Los Angeles Lakers on Sunday. ... Jones averaged 29.6 points in his previous five games.
